  "query": "How does the evidence for using acoustically reflective materials on fishing gear compare to attaching acoustically reflective objects for reducing marine mammal entanglement?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence for attaching acoustically reflective objects: Two studies (Timor Sea and Arafura Sea, Australia; Gulf of Alaska, USA) reported that metallic bead chains on nets did not reduce dolphin entanglements and acrylic beads near hooks did not reduce sperm whale predation on catches [2806]. Evidence for using acoustically reflective fishing gear materials: Five studies (Bay of Fundy, Canada; Fortune Channel, Canada; North Sea, Denmark; South Atlantic Ocean, Argentina) reported mixed outcomes, with behaviour studies showing harbour porpoises approached barium sulfate and conventional nets at similar distances and durations, with fewer echolocation clicks at barium sulfate nets and similar echolocation activity at barium sulfate versus conventional nets; and catch studies where two of three controlled studies found fewer harbour porpoise entanglements in iron-oxide or barium sulfate nets compared to conventional nets, while one study found barium sulfate nets did not reduce dolphin entanglements [2807].",
